Topic Cloud Run deployment with separate invoker/runtime service accounts and time-based conditional IAM bindings.
________________________________________
Objective Deploy a private Cloud Run service, grant invoker access via a conditional IAM binding, test allow/deny behavior, and remove the condition cleanly.
________________________________________
Key Concepts
•	Cloud Run has two separate identities: invoker SA (who can call it) and runtime SA (what it can access)
•	IAM conditions use CEL expressions evaluated at request time by GCP — not client side
•	Multiple conditions on the same member+role = access granted if ANY condition is true
•	Unconditional binding overrides conditional — access granted regardless of time/context
•	Version 3 IAM policy = conditional bindings are present
•	Audit logs (admin actions) are always on; request logs (HTTP calls) need enabling
•	--no-allow-unauthenticated blocks unauthenticated callers only — valid identity tokens still get through
•	Line wrapping in Cloud Shell breaks CEL expressions — use \ continuation or keep commands on one line
________________________________________
Practical Work Completed
•	Reused cloud-sa as runtime SA; created cr-invoker-sa as separate invoker SA
•	Deployed hello-service (private, no unauthenticated access) with cloud-sa as runtime SA
•	Granted roles/run.invoker to invoker-sa on hello-service
•	Verified unconditional binding via get-iam-policy
•	Removed unconditional binding; re-added with BusinessHours CEL condition (Mon-Fri 08-18 UTC)
•	Granted roles/iam.serviceAccountTokenCreator to ma.neizer@gmail.com to enable impersonation
•	Generated identity token impersonating invoker-sa; curled service → confirmed 403 (01:51 UTC, outside window)
•	Added temporary hourWindow condition (until 03:00 UTC); confirmed 200
•	Removed hourWindow condition cleanly using \ line continuation and full condition match including description
•	Explored Cloud Logging — identified audit logs vs request logs; confirmed request logs not enabled by default
________________________________________
Confusions / Fixes
•	user: vs serviceAccount: prefix — fixed quickly
•	Line wrapping breaking CEL expressions — resolved with \ continuation
•	Remove command required full condition match including description — not just title
•	$TOKEN not persisting between commands — fixed by storing in same session
•	Version 3 meaning — confused with update count; correct meaning is conditional bindings present
________________________________________
Mental Model Cloud Run is a two-door system. The front door (invoker) controls who can knock. The back door (runtime) controls what the service can touch inside GCP. IAM conditions are a time-lock on the front door — GCP checks the clock on every knock.
